  "riddle": "1. Seek the path traversed by a player who emerged from the gridiron of a famed Maryland institution, where he honed his craft. Which college is it?\n\n2. How high does the ground rise in the state named for a notable American revolutionary figure, famed for its crab cakes and history? \n\n3. Count the green oases that lie close to your answer from clue 2. How many parks are nearby?\n\n4. Combine the answers from clues 2 and 3. What is the sum of the elevation and the number of parks?\n\n5. Pen down the alphabetical rank of the first letter from the institution mentioned in clue 1; how many does it account for?\n\n6. Journey to a venue known for its melodic gatherings nestled in a town that shares a region with your previous college. Ascertain the height above sea level here.\n\n7. A particular football team dons the pride of a state; uncover the name of their home arena. What is it called?\n\n8. Imagine a formation where a quarterback stands behind two fellow players—how many running backs are arranged in this formation?\n\n9. Seek the elevation of the spot defined by the formation identified in clue 8. How high does it stand?\n\n10. Investigate the number of sporting arenas in proximity to the site representing clue 8. How many stadiums surround it?\n\n11. Add together the elevation from clue 9 and the stadium count from clue 10. What total do you reach?\n\n12. In a year of many choices, how many selections were recorded in the professional football draft of 1953? \n\n13. If 360°C were to be altered to find its equivalent in Fahrenheit terms, what would the offset be? \n\n14. Find the libraries that inhabit the vicinity of a Californian city known for its tech growth; how many linger near San Jose?\n\n15. Reflect upon the figure discovered in clue 14; what is the total count of its divisors?\n\n16. The final calculation is upon you: take the absolute difference between the results from clues 4 and 11, then subtract the number from clue 5. Wrap it up with a mod operation by 10: abs(clue 4 - clue 11) % 10. What single digit emerges?",
